You can use a regex with a forward lookahead which insists on an even number of characters before end-of-line, and then reverse the result of that. For example, in JS:



&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const str = &#39;abcde&#39;;

    let a = str.match(/[a-z]{1,2}(?=([a-z]{2})*$)/g).reverse();
    console.log(a);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

With regex it&#39;s not possible although for getting desired result, you can first reverse the string, then match and reverse each matched value

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let reversedMatch = (str) =&gt;{
      return str.split(&#39;&#39;)
                .reverse()
                .join(&#39;&#39;)
                .match(/[a-z]{1,2}/g)
                .map(v=&gt; v.split(&#39;&#39;).reverse().join(&#39;&#39;))
    }

    console.log(reversedMatch(&quot;abcde&quot;))

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

