You are probably getting null pointer exception which is causing crash in your app, you need to initialize your shared preferences class and the use that object as: 

    SharedPrefManager sharedPrefManager = new SharedPrefManager (getContext());
    sharedPrefManager.saveSPBoolean(SharedPrefManager.SP_SUDAH_LOGIN, false);

It&#39;s better to use **singleton design pattern** rather than every time create an object of the same class. `Singleton design pattern` restricts the `instantiation` of a class to one `single instance`.

You can create a **singleton class** for **SharedPreference** and then you can access it from any `activity` or `fragment` you want.

Example

```
public class SharedPrefManager{
  private static SessionManager jInstance;
  private final SharedPreferences prefs;
  private final SharedPreferences.Editor editor;

  // private constructor to force use of 
  // getInstance() to create Singleton object 
  private SharedPrefManager(Context context) {
      prefs = context.getSharedPreferences(&quot;Your_Preference_name&quot;, Context.MODE_PRIVATE);
      editor = prefs.edit();
  }
  
  // create the instance when it is accessed for the first time
  public static synchronized SharedPrefManager getInstance(Context context) {
      if (jInstance != null) {
          return jInstance;
      } else {
          jInstance = new SharedPrefManager(context);
          return jInstance;
      }
  }

  // for changing logged in status
  public void isLoggedIn(boolean loginStatus){
      editor.putString(&quot;is_loggedin&quot;,loginStatus);
      editor.apply();
  }

  // for checking logged in status
  public boolean isLoggedIn(){
      return prefs.getBoolean(&quot;is_loggedin&quot;,false);
  }
}
```
Now you can user `SharedPrefManager` from your fragment like below.
   
    SharedPrefManager.getInstance(context).isLoggedIn(false); // change login status
    boolean isUserLoggedIn = SharedPrefManager.getInstance(context).isLoggedIn(); // check login status.

